<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="417" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d417">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/764</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chinese Ministry of Foreign
                                    Affairs at Nanking</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Chinese
                                    Legation</gloss></hi><note n="58" xml:id="d417fn58">Copy of
                                telegram transmitted to the Department by the Chinese Legation,
                                December 10, 1932.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-10">December 10, 1932</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Minister <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CK3">Chian[g]</persName> at
                            Tokyo reported that the Soviet Ambassador informed him that General Su
                            Ping-Wen was permitted to depart <pb facs="0509" n="411" xml:id="pg_411"/> while large number of soldiers were willing to remain in the Union of
                            Socialist Soviet Republics, thus confirming Tass report.</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>